              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24797657#p24797657" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Workaround</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Does the radiation frequency of the star limit the habitability? I'm under the impression that red dwarves mostly put out infrared, which would limit the types of earth organisms that could use it.</div><br /><br />In most of the 'habitability' models, people are just looking for earth sized, approximately earth distance, approximately solar type stars. There are other things like atmosphere that are really important as you can imagine. Measuring atmospheres is super duper hard right now, and most of the data is pretty garbage.<br /><br />So yes, the type of star does limit whether the system can be habitable in practice. As does it's dynamics, etc. Too small a star and you need to be practically on top of it to stay warm, too big and you get too much radiation.

              

              
              
