              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24799245#p24799245" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">PunditGuy</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24799053#p24799053" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Nixon's Back!</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">At a theoretical speed of .10c,</div><br /><br />Ion propulsion and a swarm of nanoprobes should be able to do better than .10c after a few years of getting up to speed. I think. English major here -- is there a rocket scientist in the house?</div><br /><br />Nuclear pulse can go much higher, but it is a question of how much mass you are accelerating.  The more fuel (in this case, nuclear devices) the ship has to carry, the higher the mass and therefore requires more energy to accelerate.  From what I've seen, around 10-12% would be optimal for a ship of reasonable mass.

              

              
              
