              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24799971#p24799971" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">RGMBill</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">If we were to switch Mars and Venus in our solar system, it has been said, we'd likely have three habitable worlds.  Bigger is better further out, not so good close.</div><br /><br />The closer a planet is to its parent star, the more that star's radiation blasts apart water, and the more massive the planet has to be to retain the water components.<br /><br />Venus needed a moon to scoop off all that extra atmosphere. Mars just doesn't have the mass to hold one; if Mars were closer to the Sun, it would more resemble Mercury than Earth.

              

              
              
